Yesterday was a special day. 

After years of figuring out my “voice” in podcasting and writing, last year I decided to try and do my own thing. But of course no one ever does anything alone, not really. @briannegk named the show and listened to my endless processing and self-doubts, Eve and Lucy welcomed people every week, @jimmykaufholz edited my words and kept me from certain grammatical shame, and you helped form it and make it better and more authentic with your honest encouragement and feedback. 

Then, a few months ago @anniefdowns and her team at @tsfnetwork said they’d like to also help by offering some much-needed marketing, design, and sales support. So we got to work and prepared for launch. 

Which was why yesterday was so special. Because while I got to relaunch a show that I love very much and welcome a bunch of new people to the newsletter and podcast about some random guy, I actually got to do it with all of my favorite people (and favorite kitty). 

Thank you for allowing me to process my life in your inbox and podcast player every week. It’s a profound privilege.

Here’s every recorded moment of my first stand-up set. 

Here’s what you didn’t see: 

1- I bombed.  I’m not being coy and I actually did well but I’m embarrassed to say that…it was crickets. Not a single laugh. Standup is reeeeeally hard. Moreover, trying to find a new voice after you’ve been a public speaker for a long time is brain meltingly tough. The people who make it look easy are wizards. 
2- The community of people at @deadhorsecomedy made a scary thing so much better. Everyone was giving props after and encouraging me to do it again. I know there’s competition in comedy, but this place was about everyone getting better. 
3- My brain has been consumed with trying again. I can only go up from here. My goal for the next set is breathing during it and holding the mic closer.
